@gideon_mlawa Response from Prof. Plevris: Exclusion of intra abdominal pathology is important until the diagnosis of CVS is nailed down and of course examining the abdomen every time patient comes to hospital is important, but CVS is cyclical therefore acute abdomen does not present as CVS
@anumoly Response from Prof. Plevris: Only if indigestion present in between for symptomatic short term relief
@aramedic69 Response from Prof. Plevris: If abdominal migraine is suspected as a trigger then it can be helpful in the prodromal phase of CVS but TCAs are more specific in their effect to prevent CVS
@mohamed667 Response from Prof. Plevris: It is thought that vomiting gets worse by impairing gastric motility

@pdbyrne Response from Prof. Plevris: Abdominal migraine presents with predominantly abdominal pain and sometimes shares  the symptoms of classical migraine ( headache etc). Commoner in children. Abdominal migraine is considered a trigger only for CVS

@AJSC42 Dr Hewett's response: I use LEV 1st, Valproate (VPA) 2nd & then Lacosamide. Phenytoin still has it’s place. The SIGN guidelines recommend Phenytoin & VPA  but that’s because of the evidence. The results from the ESSET trial looking at LEV in status should back up my practice!

@AElsaddig Response from Dr Hewett: Depends on the freq. Outpts I increase every 2 weeks because of fatigue. Inpt every 72h. In status I go straight to 500mg bd or even start at 1000mg to gain control.
@innesrhynd Response from Dr Hewett: The rashes normally appear within a week. They may occur later if the drug is being increased or there’s a concurrent problem i.e. hepatic abnormality

@krishofayr Response from Dr Russell M Hewett: I refer you to the original study. A Comparison of Lorazepam, Diazepam, and Placebo for the Treatment of Out-of-Hospital Status Epilepticus. Brian K. Alldredge, Pharm.D., August 30, 2001. N Engl J Med 2001; 345:631-637
